<title type="html"><![CDATA[Forgetting The First Tashahud And Forgetting To Perform Sujud as-Sahw Before The Salaam – Shaykh Ibn Uthaymeen]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forum.salafiri.com/viewtopic.php?t=408&amp;p=437#p437"><![CDATA[
<strong><span style="font-size: 200%; line-height: normal"><span style="color: #0000FF">Forgetting The First Tashahud And Forgetting To Perform Sujud as-Sahw Before The Salaam – Shaykh Ibn Uthaymeen</span></span></strong><br /><br />Shaykh Ibn Uthaymeen was asked the following question:<br /><br /><span style="color: #FF0000">Question:</span><br /><br />وسئل فضيلة الشيخ: عن رجل نسي التشهد الأول فعلم أنه يجب عليه سجود سهو قبل السلام ولكنه نسي وسلم فما الحكم؟<br /><br />A man forgot the first tashahud and he knew that he must do the sujud as-Sahw before the salam. However, he forgot and made tasleem. So what is the ruling?<br /><br /><span style="color: #FF0000">Answer:</span><br /><br />فأجاب فضيلته بقوله: إن ذكر في زمن قريب سجد، وإن طال الفصل سقط، مثل أن لا يذكر إلا بعد مدة طويلة، فلو خرج من المسجد فإنه لا يرجع إلى المسجد ويسقط عنه<br /><br />If he remembered in a short time, he makes the sujud as-sahw. If the break was long, then it drops from him (the requirement of performing sujuh as-sahw). For example, he remembers after a long time after. So, if he left the masjid, then he does not return to the masjid. (Rather), it drops from him (the requirement of performing sujuh as-sahw).<br /><br /><em>[Majmoo al-Fatawa wa Rasaail (14/26)]</em><br /><br />Translated by<br /><br />Faisal Ibn Abdul Qaadir Ibn Hassan<br />Abu Sulaymaan<br /><br />Source: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://torontodawah.com/index.php/2015/08/28/forgetting-the-first-tashahud-and-forgetting-to-perform-sujud-as-sahw-before-the-salaam-shaykh-ibn-uthaymeen/">http://torontodawah.com/index.php/2015/ ... uthaymeen/</a><!-- m --><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forum.salafiri.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=56">Shehzad Sattar</a> — Sun Sep 18, 2016 10:36 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
